==English==
===Etymology===
The phrase comes from the world of horse race betting wherein lists of winners would be published with all non-paying positions printed in a block under the heading 'Also Ran:'.
===Noun===
# a person or animal who competed in a [[race]] but did not win
# ''fig.'' a loser; one soon to be forgotten

====Quotations====
* '''1960''': It also turned Palmer from an '''also-ran''' into a challenger. &mdash; 'Nerves of Steel', ''The New York Times'', 18 June, 1960 
* '''1978''': some of Mr. Scorsese's accomplishments have been so stunning—that it's impossible to view "The Last Waltz" as anything but an '''also-ran'''. &mdash; Janet Maslin, ''The New York Times'', review of ''The Last Waltz'', April 26, 1978 
* '''1993''': And, of course, it is also far easier, quicker, and less embarrassing to dismiss an '''also-ran''' over the phone thsn it is in person &mdash; Martin Yate , ''Hiring the Best'', Adams Media, 1993, page 58
* '''1998''': as the drug came out of the R&D laboratory, it could have been just another '''also-ran''' &mdash; Richard C Dorf, ''The Technology Management Handbook'', CRC Press, 1998, page 3-40
* '''2004''': The transition from [[comer]] to '''also-ran''' can be quick &mdash; ''The New Yorker'', August 9 &amp; 16, 2004, p.40



